==English==
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|yesternyght}}, {{m|enm|yisternight}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġiestranniht|t=yesternight}}, equivalent to {{af|en|yester-|night}}.
===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}
# {{lb|en|archaic}} [[last night|Last night]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=c.1598|author=[[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]]|title=[[s:Much_Ado_About_Nothing_(Shakespeare)|Much Ado About Nothing]]|chapter=Act IV, Scene 1|edition=|passage=What man was he talk'd with you '''yesternight''' <br> Out at your window betwixt twelve and one?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1611|title={{w|King James Version}} of the {{w|Bible}}|section=[[w:Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 31:29|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Genesis+31&version=KJV|passage=It is in the power of my hand to do you hurt: but the God of your father spake unto me '''yesternight''', saying, Take thou heed that thou speak not to Jacob either good or bad.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1820|author={{w|Walter Scott}}|title={{w|Ivanhoe}}|chapter=6|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/82/82-h/82-h.htm|passage={{...}} when the Templar crossed the hall '''yesternight''', he spoke to his Mussulman slaves in the Saracen language, which I well understand, and charged them this morning to watch the journey of the Jew {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1847|author={{w|Emily Brontë}}|title={{w|Wuthering Heights}}|chapter=29|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/768/768-h/768-h.htm|passage={{...}} she has disturbed me, night and day, through eighteen years—incessantly—remorselessly—till '''yesternight'''; and '''yesternight''' I was tranquil.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1885|author=Richard F. Burton|authorlink=Richard Francis Burton|title=The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night|publisher=The Burton Club|volume=I|chapter=xxii|page=228|passage=I came here '''yesternight''' for a call of nature and to do what none can do for me[.]}}
